{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487024"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:54:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:54:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"235"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/235"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.43,0.09,0.11,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"235"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48132"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/235"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"235"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32998"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12959"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40760"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48132"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with upper abdominal and left shoulder tip pain one day after a colonoscopy. During the procedure, a carcinoma of the caecum was identified and biopsied. On examination, her blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, pulse 105/min, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. She is tender in the epigastrium. The only abnormality on her laboratory investigations is a haemoglobin of 93 g/L (115-155). A CT scan is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute pancreatitis","Splenic injury","Postpolypectomy syndrome","Colonic haemorrhage","Perforation of the colon"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe symptoms and physical signs add up to peritoneal and diaphragmatic irritation - and the CT shows a \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenic rupture.\u003C/strong\u003E This is a rare, but well-recognised complication of colonoscopy. More frequently encountered complications include bleeding and perforation. Neither of these complications are common. Bleeding may occur in up to 6% of cases after polypectomy, but less than 1% of cases will require any form of intervention. Perforation can be more serious, but again, it is an uncommon occurrence, being seen in less than 1% of diagnostic investigations and 5% of therapeutic procedures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPostpolypectomy syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there is an area of localised perforation following a polypectomy, where the damage has been caused secondary to diathermy-induced tissue necrosis. The perforation may occur immediately at the time of the procedure or later, when the necrotic tissue sloughs away. In this case, the CT imaging clearly demonstrates a splenic injury and the investigations and physical examination findings are consistent with acute haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely given the absence of typical risk factors and the specific presentation of shoulder tip pain, which is more indicative of diaphragmatic irritation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonic haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with rectal bleeding rather than shoulder tip pain and epigastric tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforation of the colon\u003C/strong\u003E would present with signs of peritonitis and free air on imaging, which are not described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Abdominal pain after a colonoscopy must always raise the possibility of a complication of the procedure."],"references":["Church J. Complications of Colonoscopy. Gastroenterol Clin N Am. 2013; 42:639-57."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32998"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"235"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"11879"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20830"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"11879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/11879"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0f422036-cc1b-4199-bdd3-0d4091394548.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0f422036-cc1b-4199-bdd3-0d4091394548.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":578,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"20830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20830"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/I9j1KnPvqoA5k1hLPoHMn8bROsyrda.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/I9j1KnPvqoA5k1hLPoHMn8bROsyrda.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":578,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32998"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-06T21:04:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-18T09:58:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"235"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48132"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"h